text:
#ProudBlueEditorials 

This Editorial is my opinion, I alone am responsible for the content. This is my final editorial before the 2024 Presidential Election.

Let’s talk about Donald Trump, the man (monster) that he is. His heyday was the 1980s when he rose to “stardom,” if you want to call it that. I remember the news about the young billionaire in New York, he was always a hot topic. He was a narcissist then and that certainly has not changed. He called himself a Democrat back in those days. 

Let me do some comparisons to his look and talk that he does today in his hate rallies and I think you will understand what I have been thinking, HE IS STUCK IN THE 80s! He was thought then to be a great and successful businessman but if you were around back then as I was, you will recall that many of his businesses were failures. Who bankrupts a casino? Native Americans and other businessmen have been quite successful with casinos but he couldn’t be. Trump University, Trump steaks etc. all failures. How the man got a Star on the sidewalk Hollywood Walk of Fame is a mystery to me, he’s always been a jerk. He has always thought of himself as a chick magnet, but in actuality, he was a sexual predator and a rapist. He fit in well with the Epstein group. I believe Epstein was murdered to make sure he didn’t spill the beans. How did Trump get three wives? Simple, money, some women will fall for that. The only one who may have talked was Ivana and she is now buried on the grounds of his Bedminister Golf Club. Fishy, was she eliminated, her fall down the stairs sounds very Putin-like to me. Just my opinion. The other two wives, are a mystery. Why is Melania hanging around? Money? She sure doesn’t seem to enjoy being around him. 

Think about his current appearance, the clothes from the 80s, baggy suits and long ties, still wearing them today. The rally music, mostly 80’s, YMCA (these were gay guys except for the lead, Victor Willis) I wonder why he likes that song since he is so anti LGBTQIA. This is a Man’s World and I am sure you can think of more, they are mostly 80s songs. His fascination with Hannibal Lecter, the cannibal in Silence of the Lambs, I liken his fascination to Hannibal with “they are eating the cats, they are eating the dogs.” All can be tied to his hate of immigrants and  his statements that they are sent from mental institutions. Getting the picture? He loved  doing The Apprentice and firing people, he still does! I never watched the show, by the time it came out, I was so over hearing about The Donald and saw through his lying, playboy, cheating personality. Again, I say, Trump is stuck in the 80s, forty some years ago when he was a young man and in his “prime.”Trump is still living in those years. He has become worse, more dangerous and now seems to be in severe mental and physical decline. Even his niece Mary Trump has warned us about Donald, believe her. He should be silenced.

The question in my mind remains, why has the MAGA party, formally the Republican Party, latched onto this treacherous, lying man? Surely there would have been better choices in 2016, 2020 and 2024. As for 2020, he legitimately lost and has continued his lies about that. He knows he lost. If he were such a smart businessman wouldn’t you think he would know that once a company fires you, that’s it. No need to re-apply, but here we are. Any sane American knows that if he were to win the election we would be looking at the loss of our democracy. Trump is old, mentally and physically inept and not  fit to be President of the United States, not to mention a felon. In my opinion, if he were to win, he would be quickly cast aside and Vance would be president. Either way, both are willing to destroy our government and replace it with the horrors of Project 2025. author/description: Founder of Passage Press. Write at https://t.co/3NQ1Q9FbDT
text:
This week has raised some questions about personnel selection in the conservative/rw ecosystem, something that has come up before and will become a major point of contention in the event of a Trump win next week and his subsequent staffing of the administration...

How do we select good people? People who are reliable ideologically *and* characterologically? People who are smart, aligned, competent, and won't embarrass the organizations that affiliate with them?

These selection filters gets very narrow, very fast, and if we are being honest, it becomes clear that finding *good* people at scale is actually quite difficult.

Firstly, ideological alignment is necessary but insufficient. People can whinge about it all they want but optics matter. You have to know how to not raise people's alarm bells. In the context of administrative/public life you have to practice a certain amount of rhetorical and operational prudence. This cuts against the personality type of many early adopters of now au courant rw views. These types tend to be (almost pathologically) disagreeable. Those who cannot code-switch and suppress that tendency when necessary are going to cause problems and often be more trouble than they are worth.

Secondly, those who can code-switch, who can succeed in an administrative setting, and who also are aligned (i.e. have successfully resisted leftism), tend to already be professionally successful, or are well down the path to professional success, and have *a lot* to lose by openly aligning with the right and/or leaving behind their (probably very well paying) jobs for the pittance they will earn as political operatives. The perception (if not fact) that the right does not take care of its own people, makes this an incredibly difficult sell. Leaving a successful law practice, or job in finance, or in tech etc. just doesn't add up for all but a very few.

For those in this latter group, the onus is on the right to protect these people, ensure a meaningful (if not exorbitant) livelihood, and the promise that good service will be rewarded with opportunities and yes, money, once their political work is done. As Silicon Valley, eg, begins to flirt with the right, it has to be the case that those who want the right to prevail, the JD Vance wing of the right to prevail, that the appropriate incentives are in place to recruit capable and aligned people into public service who are incurring massive opportunity costs by doing so. Will a crypto rw tech bro who goes to work for Trump have a place in Silicon Valley when his term ends? There has to be a very loud signal that the answer is yes.

For the former, the onus is on the ideologically aligned poster to demonstrate that he won't embarrass people who affiliate with him. Some people should just stay posters. It is a noble and worthy role. And in fact anyone who is a poster and has ambitions beyond that, I immediately regard with suspicion. Their aspirations often overtake their political commitments and their personal loyalties. They are more likely to defect and betray the interests they previously supported. Rather than concentrating on getting stuff done, the main concern is engaging in the petty ego-driven carnival of "political influencer." You don't have to compromise your beliefs and shouldn't, but it's perfectly legitimate that the vetting of these types is much more stringent.

I don't have answers to this double problem––those who can, don't need to or want to, and those who want to carry a lot of different risks. This is only to say that the selection of personnel––particularly young people on the right––as we go through this major generational and ideological transition, is of critical importance. Personnel selection is maybe *the most* important thing for us to be thinking about. And the people in charge of personnel selection need to be taking this very seriously.

text:
More to his point, how someone refers to themselves by party when speaking to a pollster or an exit pollster can be entirely different than their registration.

It's how Trump, for instance, can win Hyde County, North Carolina, when it was majority Democratic in registration.

If you polled a registered Democrat in Hyde who supports Trump, they're very likely to tell you they're an independent, not their actual registration.

It's very tricky to use polling to model "indies" if the pollster didn't data append to the voter file so they know party registration.
